ng hundreds of thousands of American lives. Anne Case and Angus Deaton explain the overwhelming surge in these deaths and shed light on the social and economic forces that are making life harder for the working class. As the college educated become healthier and wealthier, adults without a degree are literally dying from pain and despair. Case and Deaton tie the crisis to the weakening position of labor, the growing power of corporations, and a rapacious health-care sector that redistributes working-class wages into the pockets of the wealthy. This critically important book paints a troubling portrait of the American dream in decline, and provides solutions that can rein in capitalism's excesses and make it work for everyone.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCapitalismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aDrug abusexEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aDrugsxOverdosezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aSuicidexEconomic aspectszUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  aAddiction.  aAdult.  aAfrican Americans.  aAlcoholic liver disease.  aAlcoholism.  aAmerican Capitalism.  aAmericans.  aAngus Deaton.  aBachelor's degree.  aBehalf.  aBirth cohort.  aBlood pressure.  aBowling Alone.  aBureau of Labor Statistics.  aCalculation.  aCapitalism.  aCardiovascular disease.  aCenters for Disease Control and Prevention.  aChronic pain.  aCompetition.  aConsumer.  aCrack epidemic.  aCurrent population survey (US).  aDeath certificate.  aDeath.  aDemography.  aDepression (mood).  aDeveloped country.  aDisability.  aDisaster.  aDisease.  aDrug overdose.  aEconomic growth.  aEconomic inequality.  aEconomist.  aEconomy.  aEmployment.  aEpidemic.  aFentanyl.  aGlobalization.  aGreat Recession.  aHealth care.  aHe